    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-04-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-04-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">548.D1/123</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Secretary General of the High Commission for Refugees</hi>
                        (<hi rend="italic">Jewish and Other</hi>) <hi rend="italic">Coming From
                        Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wurfbain</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="6" xml:id="d246fn6">Transmitted to the Department by the Consul at
                        Geneva in his despatch No. 869 Political, April 6; received April 21.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lausanne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-04-04">April 4,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg herewith to refer to my letter of March
                        22nd.,<note n="5a" xml:id="d246fn5a">Not printed.</note> and to take the
                    liberty of drawing your attention to the fact that the communications addressed
                    by this office to your Government on February 6th. and 21st.,<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d246fn7">Latter not found in Department files; see last paragraph of
                        instruction printed <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                    </note> concerning especially the question of passports for refugees from
                    Germany and that of the treatment of stateless refugees, have so far remained
                    without answer on the part of the Government of the United States of
                    America.</p>
                <p>As the above-mentioned questions are again to figure on the agenda of the next
                    meeting of the Governing Body of the High Commission, it would be highly
                    appreciated by this office if your Government would <pb facs="0405" n="305"
                        xml:id="pg_305"/> kindly inform the High Commissioner before that meeting of
                    the attitude it intends to adopt with regard to the afore-mentioned
                    recommendations.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>A. <hi rend="smallcaps">Wurfbain</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
